segments.text: formerly either manager or assistant city manager in Long Beach before he went to Phoenix.
So he was not a homegrown product.
You know what happened to the city planner in Long Beach?
No.
He ended up in jail.
Oh, is that right?
Yes, for fraud.
And Bob Paternoster came out from Pittsburgh to take over and give planning a good name again in Long Beach.
That was a real scandal in the Southern California planning circle.
We're getting a far field from Texas.
Moved to Fort Worth in the summer of 1964.
Was planning director under Jerry Brownlee, a Cookingham protege.
And unfortunately, about a year and nine months
After I got on the scene, Jerry Brownlee decided to look to greener pastures in private business.
And he went with the Justin family as a private venture operation.
But he was also involved with various interests in cattle
wholesale, grocery, and so on in a management role.
So he did very well for himself.
And I think it's his son.
Jerry Brownlee was very positive about planning, as of course LP Cookingham has been over the years.
We were instrumental finally in Fort Worth in getting the concept of sector planning established.
this as a device for the development of our own comprehensive plan.
The sector planning process literally said for each of some eight or nine major sectors in the city, the planning studies, in-depth planning studies would be done.
Then through a process of involving a sector planning council composed of citizens from the community, from that community,
property owners primarily, but residents in general.
We would then thrash out various aspects of the plan.
We had a general framework plan for the community in terms of housing, circulation, commercial industrial generators, and recreation facilities.
Those were the four main.
elements that we used to guide.
How had that been developed, that plan?
Well, that was primarily statements of principle rather than physical delineation.
And all that we said was, here are the observable patterns.
These are in place today.
Now, if we're going to work in a given sector, and these are certain principles that need to be observed, and which were commonly accepted about density and things of that sort.
The Gruen Plan had already been developed.
Gruen Plan had already been and gone in Fort Worth.
But had left an impact.
Had left an impact, but as people around Fort Worth were quick to point out, the Gruen Plan, or Gruen, left more grandchildren
than was a child that was living.
The Bruin Plan from Fort Worth never came to fruition.
But that, in turn, spawned lots and lots of communities that adapted the concepts to their own local situation.
In that sense, it was a very influential project.
Yes, just not so influential for Fort Worth.
The reason for that, and I arrived on the scene a couple of years after the major impact of the Gruen Plan.
The reason for that was that the Gruen Plan was subsidized by private interest and the public agencies were told, keep your nose out of it.
We don't want to hear from the public agencies.
We don't want to know anything from the public community
about what ought to be in this.
We are doing this for the business community.
And when it was all done, it was handed to the council and said, here's your plan for the CBD.
It was basically funded by the power company, wasn't it?
Correct.
Texas Electric Service Company and a couple of the banks were the prime movers in that.
I was in Victor's office in Beverly Hills about the time you went to Fort Worth,
It worked for Victor for about a year.
The plan could have been accomplished had the business interests said, we want more than just factual information about the community.
We want to involve him.
But those were not his marching orders, or that was not the way he conceived his work to be.
And of course, Victor Grun's a very strong personality.
And that project was reported at $50,000 for that CBD study.
Cheap.
Yeah, even at that time, that was a fairly cheap kind of thing.
What was lacking, though, was a sense of commitment on the part of the downtown interest to support it
when it came to such things as bridges and parking garages and the underground system and all of that.
Servicing.
That's where it fell.
Well, Victor brought to that job a lot of previous experience in shopping center design.
And he treated the CBD as a gigantic shopping center.
That's right.
And as you say, it probably would have worked if he had had the cooperation of everybody.

Well, part of that may have also been a little bit of a reaction by property owner interests in downtown who did not feel themselves completely as if they were being treated equitably by the big businesses, namely the power company and the banks.
And at that time, you have to keep in mind there were a lot of very, very small property owners in downtown Fort Worth.
I mean, there were places that had only 30 foot of building.
So to that extent, I don't know that Gruen really dealt with the dynamics of a situation, perhaps never even tried to put together in his own mind or his staff
the model of the dynamics that would be necessary in order to get these property owners all committed to something.
He felt, I'm sure, that he had the major ones, and that was sufficient.
But there were too many little ones in there that just simply thwarted things.
And not deliberately, it was just they felt they were being sort of thrown to the wolves.
Yes, and then, you know, having worked in his shop in Beverly Hills, it's clear to me that
anyone involved on that project.
I wasn't involved on that.
That was before I came into the office.
But clearly, the tradition in the office was to approach these things as a physical design project.
And anything related to economics and the social aspects of it were handled by the front office, if they were handled at all.
Oh, I see.
Well, they weren't handled in Fort Worth.
I mean, that was just...
I think it was typical of planning in general at the time.
Yeah, an awful lot of it.
And in fact, in that respect, Hal Wise was really unique in his way of doing things.
That's one reason I have a lot of appreciation for what Hal did in Austin, because even to this day, I have bumped into people in Austin who still talk about Hal Wise's work.
Whether they liked it or didn't like it, he is identified as having listened to people.
Harry Halliton was maybe a little too brusque with people.
But that was Harry's nature.
And they had a little trouble understanding this fellow from Northern California that seemed to not quite appreciate the parochialism of the Austin community.
Hal could tune into that very quickly.
Oh, yeah.
Well, he wore his cowboy boots.
Well, sure.
But he also listened to people.
And people knew that he was listening.
Harry listened, but they didn't know he was listening.
And they might arrive at the same judgment when it was all said and done, except the public didn't know that Harry was listening.
And that makes a lot of difference.
The things that happened in Fort Worth
as a result of the sector planning program was that Howard McMahon had become city manager.
He expected the sector planning program to be wrapped up in a matter of two and a half to three years.
We had said to him in our several budget proposals, if you want this plan,
to be more than a document to be sitting on your shelf.
You've got to involve the people.
If the people are going to be involved, then they have to feel ownership.
They are not going to feel ownership overnight.
And he said, well, go tell them what they need to know.
And I said, Howard, it doesn't work that way.
He said, but you have the backing of my office.
Go tell them.
I said, but Howard, they have to wrestle with the hard issues.
And they're going to come back with questions for you.
And you may find some of the questions are causing you some discomfort.
And he said, well, go tell them what the plan should be.
And philosophically, I found myself increasingly at odds with that philosophy of city government
city management, the style.
Top-down thing.
Yep, strictly top-down.
It just didn't gee with my way of doing things.

And some of that's because of Andy Force inculcating in me the sense of appreciation of listening to the public and getting them to not only speak their minds, but also to come up with ideas and suggestions

And as Andy used to say, and he came out of a background of working in New Jersey, some of the small communities in New Jersey, and he worked under Segoe for some period of time, and then moved, in fact, to Tucson to work under Segoe, originally when Segoe did the planning studies in Tucson.
But he said, you've got to listen to the people and you've got to put their ideas into the plan.
He said, if you don't,
They don't buy.
It's not theirs.
And this is what Hal would do.
It was what the city manager, Howard McMahon, said, well, take care of that.
Just put those in.
I said, don't do that just at the flipping of a switch.
It takes time to resolve these conflicting issues and points of view and ideas.
So finally, it just got to the point where we were in a real impasse.
And Howard and I had a real set to.
And I said, Howard, you're the city manager.
You run it the way you want to.

But I tell you right now, development of a sector plan, of sector plans and a program for the city of Fort Worth is probably going to take, realistically, within the manpower allocations that you have permitted us to have set up, probably going to take six to seven years.
And he said, it's got to be done in half that time at the outside.
And I said, well, I'm telling you.
Here's my resignation.
And I went into private practice at that point.
And that was in 1969.
Interestingly enough, it was within about two months of the seven years that the last of the sector plan studies had been
processed, gone through the community, and were adopted by the City Planning Commission from the date we started.
So I felt very satisfied that my time estimates were right.
And this was in spite of the fact that Howard then pumped about another $50,000 to $80,000 a year, successively each year, that much more, into the Long Range Planning Program in Fort Worth.
But it still took that.
kind of time, not because of the lack of technical support.
It was the time required for citizens to digest material and make up their minds and ask questions and resolve issues and come back and say, this is what we want.
For any plan of this nature, it's about a year gestation time.
Sure.
And see, what we were doing was starting a new, we programmed it to start a new sector study
every four to six months.

And my successor, David Farrington, who was really an engineer who didn't understand a lot of things about the planning process, and then he kind of left him because he saw greener pastures elsewhere.
Then George Human, who was assistant city manager, took over.
And George was the one who was kind enough to send me a copy
of the newspaper notice that said that the sector planning program has now come full circle.
George is a nice guy.
Oh, yeah, he is.
He really is.
He had more understanding of the nature of the planning process than... Farrington.
Farrington.
Farrington.
All he saw was the engineering considerations.
Do you know when George took over as planning director in Fort Worth?
Wasn't that about 19...
71 or so?
It would have been close to that, yes.
Late 70 or early 71.
And then after George?
I don't know who was in there then after that.
My predecessor was William Jennings Bryan Baker and he had been there for five years and Bryan was not a
He was a good talker, but I think he often found himself crosswise with the city council and other officials.
But he lasted exactly five years to the day.
By way of a flashback, reflecting on the Tucson situation, Andy Ford had come there under Laszlo Seiko.
having previously worked under Segoe in New Jersey on some town planning assignments, and particularly in Montclair, New Jersey.
And then really what I saw in Segoe's work in Tucson, which was for Tucson and Pima County, was a product that was imbued with a lot of caring about the community.
at the same time with some very strong, strong recommendations about such things as thoroughfare, street standards, standards for protection of floodplain areas and things of that sort.
In fact, Segal was in some respect way ahead of his day talking about flood hazards out in the desert.
People just didn't believe him.
They wouldn't listen to him at that time.
And Andy...
for was very much of a person who would bring up a topic that Segoe had identified.
And he would say, no, wait a minute.
Let's look at this.
He'd say this in the middle of a planning commission meeting.
And a very illustrative example of something occurred one time in Tucson, a subdivider was
had been told in the review of the subdivision plan, or the preliminary plan, you must provide your half of this 150-foot right-of-way or 160-foot right-of-way along this major street.
And I don't remember what road it was.
It's not important.
Do you want all this?
Yeah.
The point is that the man protested to the city council and said the city has never adopted that comprehensive plan.
The city has never adopted the third streets and highways plan.
The issue, the council, of course, was on tenterhooks.
What do we do?
They turned it over to the city attorney, and the city attorney came right back and said, you don't have to have adopted that.
Your planning commission has been observing it.
You have been ratifying it with every subdivision plat that you've approved in accordance with state law.
You have insisted that every developer along the way adhere to the standards that are enunciated in that plan, and that plan has been well known in the community for six, seven, eight years.
You are on perfectly solid ground.
The man took the issue to court, and the court sustained the position of the city attorney.
They said, in fact, the city council had adopted the plan because over and over, in their actions,
they had referred to the plan as their official guide.
Sort of like a common law marriage.
That's right, very much so.

And I think I gained a lot of respect for Andy Ford at that point because he saw this as a bond, if you will, between reflected in community policy between the official actions on the one hand and the advisory actions on the other.
And one other thing that Andy did do, which I appreciated very much,
He taught me very well how to do minutes of meetings.
And he had a little trick that he used that came out of his experience in New England town meetings when he lived up in New England.
Because the New England town meeting sometimes gets to be kind of disjointed.
He said there were three actions that you could report, either how something was voted, how it was agreed upon,
or what the consensus was.
And he said, those are the three key words that you put in your minutes.
And he said, once the minutes are ratified by the body at the next meeting or whenever, that's just as good as any binding formal vote.
And I have lived by that over the years since.
And when I went to Austin, we developed the minutes so that it was reflected such and such was voted to recommend or to

approve or whatever and if it was simply an agreement it was agreed colon that so and so or if it was a situation where there wasn't any apparent agreement it appeared to be the consensus colon that so and so would be done and that resolved the matter and uh i talked with city attorneys various times uh when i show them this and boy they were just tickled to death they said these have been adopted i said yes
I said, okay, that's all we need to know.
So Andy Ford, because of experience under CEDAW, really carried down a lot of things for me.
I was involved in a couple of things while I was in Fort Worth.
One was a very active role in setting up the North Central Texas Council of Governments as a staff person.
There were several of us from Dallas and Fort Worth and some of the other cities that took an active role in that.
And I was really the one responsible to the city manager for the city of Fort Worth's part in the background work leading up to COG being established.
I was also involved uniquely because of the research interests that I had in the effort to get
the School of Social Work established at UT Arlington.
And I was also involved in establishing, in a way, the planning program at the School of Architecture at UT Arlington.
Particularly in heading the committee that Bob Wagner referred to, trying to come up with some basic criteria
for incorporation into the curriculum.
That was with Bill Shevlin.
That's right.
Bill was on that, and frankly, I don't remember who all the other people were.
There were quite a few of us that were involved.
Bob was involved.
Bob Wagner was involved in that.
Shevlin was involved.
I was.
Springer provided some background in that.
I don't remember who the others were, but there were half a dozen people that were involved in one fashion or other.
And it was finally up to me to develop the final recommendations as they went into UT.
So I felt, in a lot of ways, my contributions sort of hit a number of areas.
The social work area and research area, I'd been involved at TCU in the urban studies program.
teaching there in the planning courses, and then at SMU teaching in the planning courses through real estate and regional science.
How do you view the current state of planning in Texas today?
Frankly, I'm not as happy with the situation or as comfortable with it as I would like to be.
On the one hand, Bob, I see the planning not being allowed to really move out and deal with issues as they need to be dealt with.
I see some of these neighborhood problems here in Dallas, for example, where, of course, Dallas has a history of let the developer control the situation.
I don't read in the newspaper the identification of the planning function as being intimately involved with the concerns of what happens in the neighborhood.
That's not a fair assessment because I know they are, or at least I think they are.
But on the other hand, I don't find that the newspapers
are identifying the planning function as one that is in the middle of trying to help deal with the critical issues.
It's the neighborhood group versus the developer instead of where's the planner in all of this, other than the private planner for the developer.
It sounds like we don't have much PR.
That's one of the problems, certainly.
The other, though, I guess I'm still suspicious.
I say suspicious.
That may not be the best word.
But I still have some negative feelings about the way planning functions in a council manager city.
Not that it's remote from the manager, but that the manager is pressed so hard, as is all corporate business in America, to worry about

this next quarter's bottom line report or next mid-year report or next year's report on bottom line that the manager and his staff or her staff are constantly driven by the dollar signs on the budget and not driven by issues that are concerned with
the dollar signs five years and ten years from now.
A case of incompatible time horizons.
Oh, very much so.
Very much so.
The planner, by nature, is not looking at this quarterly report.
I mean, even a subdivision approval is not looking at that quarterly report.
Oh, no, it's very long range.
A zoning change is not looking at the quarterly report.
At best, it's looking at six months or...
nine months or a year from now.
So I think this is the one shortcoming.
The other is that managers themselves, as I see it, have not been schooled in the philosophy of long-range planning for their communities.
And they seem to be reflecting instead
at least on the operational side, the attitudes of the Harvard Graduate School of Business.
We are a large corporate structure.
Run it like a business.
Run it like a business, yeah.
And don't bother the people at top with the problems of the people in the community at large.
After all, they're the taxpayers, but our job is to do the best professional job we can to run the city
not provide the best community for them.
Do you think the role of state government in Texas with regard to planning has been adequate?
No, quite frankly.
The brightest star on the horizon is the formation, or was the formation, and still remains, the councils of government.
I don't...
However, the quality of that varies across the state.
Within our own area... You've done quite well.
North Central Texas' cog, which was the first one in the state, has really done a beautiful job.
I cannot fault conceptually what they have been able to do.
I'm not sure that I agree with Bill Pitstick, whom incidentally I shared classes with at UT Austin one time.
But I...
Bill's style is again somewhat related to the council manager's style in the way he runs things.

But because COGs are what they are structurally in terms of governmental relationships, the governmental respondents or participants, a mayor, a councilman, a regional representative, they are really responsible to
for the whole entity and they're responsible in a sense to each other as well as their own personal constituency.
That puts the COGS in a different working relationship than does a city council under a council manager plan.
But what about the state government itself rather than COGS?
What about the role of the state legislature vis-a-vis planning legislation, for example?
I don't see much positive support.
And I may be very negative about this.
I don't see much positive support coming out of the legislature for planning.
I think as a state, we are still, well, we're not quite in the wild west, but we're not from that strong individualism.
Don't bother the man.
or the woman who's trying to do something to pull himself or herself up our own bootstraps.
Don't bug anybody.
Let me ask you next what your views are on planning education in Texas.
Bob, I guess there's several things that ought to be said.
One is I did.
do part of my graduate work in the planning program.
